Relationships among trauma exposure, chronic posttraumatic stress disorder 
symptoms, and self-reported health in women: replication and extension.

Kimerling R(1), Clum GA, Wolfe J.

Author information:
(1)Department of Psychiatry, University of California, San Francisco School of 
Medicine, USA.

Fifty-two women who served during the Vietnam era were assessed for war-zone 
exposure, traumatic life events, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and 
self-reported health status. Symptoms of PTSD were examined as mediators in the 
relationship between traumatic exposure and subsequent reports of health 
problems. Results showed that PTSD symptoms accounted significantly for variance 
in health problems reported by women with prior traumatic stressor exposure. 
When the cardinal symptom domains of PTSD (re-experiencing, numbing, avoidance, 
hyper-arousal) were analyzed separately, the symptom cluster representing 
hyper-arousal accounted uniquely for the variance associated with health 
complaints, beyond that contributed by other symptom clusters. Discussion of the 
results focuses on mechanisms underlying the relationship between specific 
symptoms of PTSD and self-reported health. Implications for intervention within 
the medical system are also considered.

